### PR summary [07e9b7ad8f](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/21829/commits/07e9b7ad8f2e366f70e7318c9fa437d1cadeca9d)

No significant changes to the import graph

|Files|Import difference|

</details>

---

<details><summary>

#### Declarations diff

</summary>

`+ Module.Hom.Tensor`
`+ homTensorHomMap_bij:`
`+ homTensorHomMap_inj`
`+ homTensorHomMap_surj:`
<details>
  <summary>You can run this locally as follows</summary>


```bash
## summary with just the declaration names:
./scripts/declarations_diff.sh <optional_commit>

## more verbose report:
./scripts/declarations_diff.sh long <optional_commit>
```
</details>

The doc-module for `script/declarations_diff.sh` contains some details about this script.

</details>

---

<details><summary>No changes to technical debt.</summary>

You can run this locally as
```
./scripts/technical-debt-metrics.sh pr_summary
```
* The `relative` value is the weighted *sum* of the differences with weight given by the *inverse* of the current value of the statistic.
* The `absolute` value is the `relative` value divided by the total sum of the inverses of the current values (i.e. the weighted *average* of the differences).
</details>

I am not really sure about having all these private lemmas. Everything up to `tensor_inclusion2_inj` seems quite useless to me. They are mostly only used once below and could be dealt with in line. And `tensor_inclusion2_inj` itself is a general statement saying that surjective maps are epi.

I am not really sure about having all these private lemmas. Everything up to `tensor_inclusion2_inj` seems quite useless to me. They are mostly only used once below and could be dealt with in line. And `tensor_inclusion2_inj` itself is a general statement saying that surjective maps are epi.
You probably shouldn't start wit this. You should start with an arbitrary free module and these splittings. And specialize to finite projective modules in the ned.
but I thought the whole file is about finite projective modules?
Yes but this should work for arbitrary splittings of projective modules, not only the one obtained by choice.
done!

```suggestion
This file proves that for `M` and `N` finitely generated projective
```

```suggestion
modules over a commutative ring `R`, the tensor product of the hom module
```

```suggestion
from `M` to `P` and the one from `N` to `Q` for `P`, `Q` being arbitrary
```
Remove?
yes that was a mistake
deleted

I don't think you can make a definition in the root namespace with a name like that. If you `open LinearMap` then `lcomp _ _ f0` is shorter than `inclusion1 R M P M' f0` anyway so this "abbreviation" is actually making things longer?
it's deleted!

```suggestion
  TensorProduct.map (f0.lcomp R P) (f0'.lcomp R Q)
```
is shorter. Why not put this abbrev in some `TensorProduct` namespace and give it a better name? It has nothing to do with inclusions as far as I can see.
I'm probably gonna make this `private`...
deleted this `abbrev`!
Can you remove this non-terminal `simp`?
removed!
I think these names are not suitable for mathlib. The naming convention doesn't say anything about 1's. Why can't we just follow the naming convention with these lemmas?
I've marked them `private` but I'm happy to change names! (I'm terrible at naming stuff...:(()

```suggestion
def Module.Hom.Tensor : (M [R] P) [R] (N [R] Q) [R] (M [R] N [R] P [R] Q) :=
```
and everywhere else

```suggestion
`TensorProduct.homTensorHomMap`, this could also be seen as a generalisation of
`homTensorHomEquiv`. -/
```

```suggestion
private lemma comm_square3 : (homTensorHomEquiv R _ _ _ _).toLinearMap 
```

pullRequest.title: feat(LinearAlgebra/TensorProduct/HomTensor): Add TensorProduct of Hom-modules
